---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
---
<Layout title="Home" description="patinate renders Strava activity into stylized heatmap posters. Streets ridden often appear bright; streets ridden once appear faint. The patina builds where you ride.">
  <header class="hero">
    <img class="hero-glyph" src="/hero-glyph.svg" alt="" aria-hidden="true" />
    <p class="page-eyebrow">vol 0.1 · strava → poster</p>
    <h1 class="hero-title">a field of routes.</h1>
    <p class="hero-lede">
      Strava activity rendered as a stylized heatmap. Streets ridden
      often appear <em>bright</em>; streets ridden once appear faint.
      The patina builds where you ride.
    </p>
    <p class="hero-tagline">a poster of your year, drawn by your feet.</p>
    <div class="hero-cta">
      <a class="cta-primary" href="https://gitlab.com/dunn.dev/patinate">Read on GitLab →</a>
      <a class="cta-secondary" href="https://gitlab.com/dunn.dev/patinate/-/releases">Releases</a>
    </div>
  </header>

  <section>
    <h2 class="section-title">How it runs</h2>
    <p class="section-prose">
      Patinate is four small commands that pipe into each other. The
      design intent is that no part of it owns long-running state of
      its own — Strava and OpenStreetMap own the upstream data, your
      disk owns the cache, and the renderer is a pure function of
      what's on disk at the moment you run it. You should be able to
      delete <code>~/.config/patinate</code>, re-run the four
      commands, and get a poster byte-equivalent to the one you had
      yesterday.
    </p>
    <figure class="diagram pipeline-figure">
      <img class="pipeline-wide" src="/pipeline.svg" alt="Pipeline diagram. Four CLI commands run left to right. patinate auth performs a one-time OAuth handshake with Strava and writes a refresh token into the local config. patinate fetch-osm pulls the city basemap from the Overpass API once per city and writes a gzipped JSON cache. patinate sync pulls new activities from Strava into a local SQLite cache, incrementally on every run. patinate render reads the config, the OSM cache, and the activity cache and writes a poster as SVG or PNG." />
      <img class="pipeline-narrow" src="/pipeline-narrow.svg" alt="Pipeline diagram. Four CLI commands stacked top-to-bottom. patinate auth performs a one-time OAuth handshake with Strava and writes a refresh token into the local config. patinate fetch-osm pulls the city basemap from the Overpass API once per city and writes a gzipped JSON cache. patinate sync pulls new activities from Strava into a local SQLite cache, incrementally on every run. patinate render reads all three caches and writes a poster as SVG or PNG." />
      <p class="diagram-caption">four commands · three caches · one poster</p>
    </figure>
    <p class="section-prose">
      <code>auth</code> runs once, writes a refresh token; from then
      on the cached token quietly re-rolls. <code>fetch-osm</code>
      runs once per city — the basemap is just streets and water and
      doesn't change between two of your rides. <code>sync</code> is
      the only command you re-run often; it walks the Strava
      activities API one page at a time at human pace and only pulls
      what's new since last time. <code>render</code> reads all
      three caches and composes the poster — no network calls, no
      surprises, theme picked by flag.
    </p>
    <div class="tile-grid">
      <div class="tile">
        <p class="tile-eyebrow">flow · in</p>
        <p class="tile-headline">activities</p>
        <p class="tile-prose">
          Strava OAuth → polyline + segments + timestamps. Incremental
          sync (only new activities since the last run), cached
          locally as JSON. OSM basemap fetched once per city and
          pinned by tile-bbox hash.
        </p>
        <p class="tile-meta">oauth · incremental · cached</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tile">
        <p class="tile-eyebrow">discipline · posture</p>
        <p class="tile-headline">private</p>
        <p class="tile-prose">
          Home-coordinate obfuscation: every polyline endpoint within
          a configurable radius of your home is snapped to a point on
          the radius circle, so the poster never reveals where you
          live. Segment names stripped, athlete and gear IDs zeroed
          in the bundled fixture.
        </p>
        <p class="tile-meta">circle-obfuscate · 1km+ default</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tile">
        <p class="tile-eyebrow">flow · out</p>
        <p class="tile-headline">posters</p>
        <p class="tile-prose">
          Stylized SVG (vector — print at any size) plus a PNG render
          via <code>resvg</code>. Four themes ship in tree; each is a
          single JSON file declaring road widths, colors, and
          heat-stroke alpha so adding a fifth theme is a one-file
          change.
        </p>
        <p class="tile-meta">noir · blueprint · warm-beige · cycle</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tile">
        <p class="tile-eyebrow">discipline · lifetime</p>
        <p class="tile-headline">local</p>
        <p class="tile-prose">
          One operator, one laptop, one set of Strava credentials. No
          telemetry, no upload, no shared identifiers. The basemap is
          OSM tiles cached on disk; the routes are yours; the
          rendered poster is yours; the binary is the only process.
        </p>
        <p class="tile-meta">one operator · no telemetry</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2 class="section-title">A year on the map</h2>
    <p class="section-prose">
      The bundled fixture rendered live with
      <code>patinate render --theme cycle_heat --web --transparent-bg</code>.
      Filter by activity type to fade the rest into the patina, the
      way overlapping strokes accumulate when you ride.
    </p>
    <figure class="diagram print-frame">
      <div class="heatmap-host" id="heatmap" aria-label="Live patinate heatmap rendering of the Grand Rapids fixture set."></div>
      <p class="print-caption">
        <span>cycle_heat · --web --transparent-bg</span>
        <span>42.96°N 85.67°W</span>
      </p>
    </figure>
    <div class="filter-chips" role="group" aria-label="Activity type filter">
      <button type="button" data-filter="all" aria-pressed="true">All types <span class="count" id="count-all">—</span></button>
      <button type="button" data-filter="Ride" aria-pressed="false">Ride <span class="count" id="count-Ride">—</span></button>
      <button type="button" data-filter="EBikeRide" aria-pressed="false">E-bike <span class="count" id="count-EBikeRide">—</span></button>
      <button type="button" data-filter="Run" aria-pressed="false">Run <span class="count" id="count-Run">—</span></button>
      <button type="button" data-filter="Walk" aria-pressed="false">Walk <span class="count" id="count-Walk">—</span></button>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2 class="section-title">Four themes</h2>
    <p class="section-prose">
      The same Grand Rapids fixture rendered through each of the
      four bundled themes. Pick one with <code>--theme &lt;name&gt;</code>;
      ship a different print of the same year by changing only the
      flag.
    </p>
    <div class="tile-grid">
      <figure class="tile theme-tile">
        <img src="/theme-noir_heat.png" alt="patinate render with the noir_heat theme: a black canvas with orange heat trails over a dim white road network." />
        <figcaption>
          <p class="tile-eyebrow">theme</p>
          <p class="tile-headline">noir_heat</p>
          <p class="tile-prose">Black canvas, orange heat. The high-contrast print.</p>
        </figcaption>
      </figure>
      <figure class="tile theme-tile">
        <img src="/theme-blueprint_heat.png" alt="patinate render with the blueprint_heat theme: a deep blue canvas with white routes." />
        <figcaption>
          <p class="tile-eyebrow">theme</p>
          <p class="tile-headline">blueprint_heat</p>
          <p class="tile-prose">Deep blue canvas, white routes. The engineering-drawing print.</p>
        </figcaption>
      </figure>
      <figure class="tile theme-tile">
        <img src="/theme-warm_beige.png" alt="patinate render with the warm_beige theme: a paper-warm canvas with dark ink roads and orange heat." />
        <figcaption>
          <p class="tile-eyebrow">theme</p>
          <p class="tile-headline">warm_beige</p>
          <p class="tile-prose">Paper canvas, dark ink, orange heat. The annual-report print.</p>
        </figcaption>
      </figure>
      <figure class="tile theme-tile">
        <img src="/theme-cycle_heat.png" alt="patinate render with the cycle_heat theme: a cream canvas with steel-blue heat over light tan roads." />
        <figcaption>
          <p class="tile-eyebrow">theme</p>
          <p class="tile-headline">cycle_heat</p>
          <p class="tile-prose">Cream canvas, steel-blue heat. The editorial print.</p>
        </figcaption>
      </figure>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2 class="section-title">Install</h2>
    <p class="section-prose">
      Two ways to run <code>patinate</code>, in increasing order of
      isolation from your day-to-day machine. Each release ships
      cosign-signed binaries, a CycloneDX SBOM per architecture, and
      a SLSA v1.0 provenance attestation, all verifiable against
      GitLab's OIDC issuer.
    </p>
    <div class="tile-list">
      <div class="tile">
        <p class="tile-eyebrow">option a</p>
        <h3 class="tile-headline">Cargo install</h3>
        <pre>cargo install patinate</pre>
        <p class="tile-prose">
          Build from source against your local Rust toolchain. Needs
          a C compiler for the resvg PNG path
          (<code>build-essential</code> on Debian, <code>xcode-select --install</code>
          on macOS). No external runtime deps. Best for contributors
          and anyone who already runs Rust for other work.
        </p>
        <p class="tile-meta">rust 1.75+ · resvg · cc required</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tile">
        <p class="tile-eyebrow">option b</p>
        <h3 class="tile-headline">Prebuilt binary</h3>
        <pre>curl -L -o patinate https://gitlab.com/dunn.dev/patinate/-/releases/permalink/latest/downloads/patinate-linux-amd64</pre>
        <p class="tile-prose">
          Cosign-signed binary from the
          <a href="https://gitlab.com/dunn.dev/patinate/-/releases">releases page</a>.
          Pair the download with the matching <code>.sig</code> and
          verify against the GitLab OIDC issuer before running. The
          hardened option that doesn't ask you to install a Rust
          toolchain.
        </p>
        <p class="tile-meta">linux/amd64 · linux/arm64 · darwin/arm64 · cosign</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2 class="section-title">Provenance</h2>
    <p class="section-prose">
      The plate above is the bundled <code>fixtures/activities.json</code>,
      sourced from public Strava cycling and running segments for
      Grand Rapids — not any rider's personal activity. Athlete IDs
      are zeroed, gear IDs are placeholders, segment names are
      generic identifiers. The repo ships zero real-rider data and
      zero maintainer-attributable coordinates. The same applies to
      anything you render: only the operator's own Strava activities
      are touched, only on the operator's own machine.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2 class="section-title">Who this is for</h2>
    <p class="section-prose">
      A cyclist, runner, or walker who tracks on Strava and wants a
      <em>specific image</em> — a poster of the year, an end-of-month
      snapshot for a holiday card, a printed map of the streets they
      know by feet. <code>patinate render</code> makes the image once;
      what you do with it (frame it, print it, embed it on a page
      that refreshes every Sunday) is up to you. The
      <code>--web --transparent-bg</code> flags exist precisely so a
      scheduled run can drop a fresh SVG into a site's static assets.
    </p>
    <p class="section-prose">
      If your activities live somewhere else, or if you're happy
      enough with Strava's own annual visualizations,
      <code>patinate</code> is not for you. It's also not a
      visualization service — there is no upload, no shared
      identifier, no aggregation across riders. One operator, one
      laptop, one poster.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2 class="section-title">Collaborate</h2>
    <p class="section-prose">
      <code>patinate</code> ships small on purpose, but the surface
      is wide. There are obvious next moves the maintainer hasn't
      gotten to yet, and they're all good first issues if you want
      to send a patch.
    </p>
    <div class="tile-list">
      <div class="tile">
        <p class="tile-eyebrow">contribute</p>
        <h3 class="tile-headline">a fifth theme</h3>
        <p class="tile-prose">
          Themes are single JSON files declaring road widths, colors,
          and heat-stroke alpha. <code>themes/your_idea.json</code>
          plus a screenshot in the MR is the whole change. The four
          shipping themes cover noir, blueprint, paper, and
          editorial — what's missing is a high-contrast print, a
          full-color terrain, a single-route minimalist poster.
        </p>
        <p class="tile-meta">themes/*.json · one file · drop a screenshot</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tile">
        <p class="tile-eyebrow">contribute</p>
        <h3 class="tile-headline">a non-Strava source</h3>
        <p class="tile-prose">
          The sync layer is a thin adapter that walks an activities
          API and writes polylines into the cache. A second adapter
          for Garmin Connect, Komoot, RideWithGPS, or a self-hosted
          source would let the same render pipeline serve a wider
          audience. The renderer doesn't care where the polylines
          came from.
        </p>
        <p class="tile-meta">src/strava → src/sources/*</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tile">
        <p class="tile-eyebrow">contribute</p>
        <h3 class="tile-headline">a second basemap</h3>
        <p class="tile-prose">
          OSM via Overpass is the only basemap source today. A
          Mapbox or Maplibre-vector adapter would unlock fancier
          typographic basemaps; a custom hand-drawn SVG basemap
          adapter would unlock printed-art posters of your home
          neighborhood with no roads at all, just the heat.
        </p>
        <p class="tile-meta">src/osm → src/basemap/*</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tile">
        <p class="tile-eyebrow">contribute</p>
        <h3 class="tile-headline">an issue, a fixture, a print</h3>
        <p class="tile-prose">
          If you ran patinate and the output surprised you, file an
          <a href="https://gitlab.com/dunn.dev/patinate/-/issues">issue</a>
          with the theme name and the activity-type counts. If you
          made a poster you like, send a low-resolution screenshot
          for the gallery. Either way, you'll be making the next
          person's first run smoother.
        </p>
        <p class="tile-meta">issues · gallery · fixtures</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <p class="section-prose" style="margin-top: var(--space-5)">
      Read <a href="https://gitlab.com/dunn.dev/patinate/-/blob/main/CONTRIBUTING.md">CONTRIBUTING.md</a>
      before sending the first patch — it covers the privacy posture
      (no real-rider coordinates in test fixtures, ever) and the
      release shape. Then open an MR; small ones land fast.
    </p>
  </section>
</Layout>

<script>
  (async () => {
    const root = document.getElementById('heatmap');
    if (!root) return;
    let svg;
    try {
      const resp = await fetch('/heatmap-web.svg');
      if (!resp.ok) throw new Error(`fetch heatmap-web.svg: ${resp.status}`);
      root.innerHTML = await resp.text();
      svg = root.querySelector('svg');
      if (!svg) throw new Error('no <svg> element');
      svg.removeAttribute('width');
      svg.removeAttribute('height');
      svg.setAttribute('preserveAspectRatio', 'xMidYMid slice');
    } catch (err) {
      root.innerHTML = `<p style="font-family:var(--font-mono); padding:2rem; color:#fff;">heatmap unavailable: ${(err as Error).message}</p>`;
      return;
    }

    const paths = svg.querySelectorAll('.heat path[data-type]');
    const counts: Record<string, number> = { all: paths.length };
    paths.forEach((p) => {
      const t = p.getAttribute('data-type') || '';
      counts[t] = (counts[t] || 0) + 1;
    });
    for (const [type, n] of Object.entries(counts)) {
      const el = document.getElementById(`count-${type}`);
      if (el) el.textContent = String(n).padStart(3, '0');
    }

    const buttons = document.querySelectorAll<HTMLButtonElement>('[data-filter]');
    const apply = (type: string) => {
      paths.forEach((p) => {
        const match = type === 'all' || p.getAttribute('data-type') === type;
        (p as SVGPathElement).style.opacity = match ? '' : '0.06';
      });
    };
    buttons.forEach((btn) => {
      btn.addEventListener('click', () => {
        buttons.forEach((b) => b.setAttribute('aria-pressed', String(b === btn)));
        apply(btn.dataset.filter || 'all');
      });
    });
  })();
</script>
